  "prompt": "Why can South Indians not accept Hindi as the national language of India?",
  "response": "This is a sensitive and complex issue. Many South Indians oppose Hindi as a national language due to:\n\n1. Linguistic differences\n- South Indian languages are Dravidian\n- Hindi belongs to Indo-Aryan language family\n- Vastly different linguistic roots and structures\n\n2. Historical resistance\n- Perceived Hindi imposition by North Indian political groups\n- Concerns about cultural domination\n- Anti-Hindi agitations in Tamil Nadu since 1930s\n\n3. Constitutional provisions\n- India has no official \"national language\"\n- Constitution recognizes multiple official languages\n- English and Hindi used for official communication\n\n4. Cultural identity preservation\n- Language seen as crucial to regional cultural identity\n- Fear of linguistic marginalization\n- Strong regional language pride\n\n5. Practical communication challenges\n- Most South Indians do not speak Hindi fluently\n- Prefer English as link language\n- Resistance to mandatory Hindi learning\n\nThis perspective reflects genuine linguistic and cultural concerns rather than simple opposition.",
